  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Reflections at My Lodging
  author: Hong Eon-jung
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I remember the journey here—snow and wind swirled thick,
    yet in Chang'an's walls, the flowers had already fallen.
    Laid low by illness in the back lanes of the city,
    what carriage wheels would trouble themselves with my solitude?

    In my chest I search through old poems and manuscripts,
    while in dreams I wander through mountains and streams.
    There are rare few who share this melancholy with me,
    walking back and forth, conversing in kindred spirit—
    no one in this world equals the old man of the East.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Chang'an refers to the ancient capital, here representing any great city center
  - key: ''
    value: The 'old man of the East' (東里老) is a poetic reference to a recluse or sage who lived apart from worldly affairs
